,Recommended,248650,8405826,"Posted: 29 December, 2013",all,Cactus,"A few days ago I picked up Draw a Stickman:EPIC on Steam sales. How did it turn out? Definitely it is a cute game. The locations look like they were drawn on recycled paper, which adds to the charm. The monsters and objects in the game are drawn very cute – the dragons almost seem huggable – but trust me, they’re not, same as the bees. Only the bunnies are innocent, but the for some devilish people it’s possible to hack them away with an ax or incinerate them. Many ways to kill a poor bunny!The drawing system in the game are somewhat hectic. I didn’t like it when I was drawing my stickman, the mouse cursor was pointing at one pixel and the dot was being created elsewhere… Quite hard to draw a decent-looking stickman this way, and I think even using my drawing tablet would not improve the precision as it was the pen tool itself having problems. Other complaint is that it could have been less square-ish when drawing the stickmen, some people actually wanted to make them nice, hey! In game I didn’t notice the wonkiness so much, but it also mattered far less. You don’t even have to draw a proper cloud with all the half-circles on the edge, it can be a plain oval and still will be a rain cloud. Fire could be a few strokes of pencil instead of a flame and still would work out as one.Other complaint would be the walking. When I would point the way with my mouse, mr Stickman would often end up getting stuck in something in the way, even if originally the path was clear. Towards the end of the game I found out (accidentally by laying an elbow on the keyboard) that he can be moved with WASD/the arrow keys. That one actually seems to works much nicer, as long as you can predict how mr Stickman would move – so I guess having the legs drawn properly is essential.The adventures themselves… in the intro you draw your friend and I would advise that you draw him or her properly, unless you want to spend the entire rest of your journey in the search of a gooeyling or something alike. The first few maps are very relaxing and fun. Then suddenly… This map can kill me? Ouch. Dragons like stickman lunch? Not flame retardant? Bees in my face? Ouch ouch ouch. Such a sudden transition from easy to hard is not too good, the devs should have made the difficulty climb rather than it becoming a huge jump. There is also that element of tedium when you end up being eaten right at the end of a map and have to do it all over again from the beginning. One would like to see some sort of checkpoints there instead of it being just on the beginning of the level. The puzzles themselves are mostly entertaining. Some solutions actually make you smile. Some others may make you want to pull your hair out. Controlling robots is tricky for example. Sometimes there is more than one way to solve a problem, which I found nice. The game has lots of hidden content as well – sometimes hidden too well, that you either find it by accident or some ingenious enlightenment.One thing that I discovered when I decided to listen to the game sound. Somehow I only liked the Stickopolis theme, rest sounded a bit annoying to me. Also the clicking sound of the pencils is not something that I consider nice, but that can be turned off, so not considering it as a major flaw.I would recommend picking this game up while it is on the sale, for the price it’s listed it’s worth. It’s a light game for killing the time, for people with some gaming experience it’s quite relaxing. For casuals it might come hard at some points, but if they don’t give up too easily, they could enjoy it as well.Pros: cute art, riddles, hidden content, fun storyCons: wonky drawing controls, movement issues, lack of balanced difficulty raising"
